Combination of polls
	Combination of polls
		A Minister of the Crown may by order make provision for the combination ofpolls at a referendum held in pursuance of an order under section 1 or 2(2)with one another or with—
			polls at a referendum held under section 27 of the Local Government Act[2000 (c. 22)](/id/ukpga/2000/22?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") or byvirtue of regulations or an order under Part 2 of that Act;
			polls at any election.
		The order may—
			make provision in connection with the combination of polls;
			make provision for the creation of offences;
			apply or incorporate with or without modifications or exceptions anyprovision of any enactment (whenever passed or made) relating to elections orreferendums.

Part 3Advice of Electoral Commission
	Advice of the Electoral Commission
		This section applies in relation to a region if—
			a referendum has been held in the region in pursuance of an order undersection 1, and
			the Secretary of State proposes that an elected assembly is established forthe region.
		Not later than the end of the period of two years beginning with the day onwhich the referendum was held the Secretary of State must give the ElectoralCommission a direction in respect of a region in relation to which thissection applies.
		A direction under subsection (2) must require the Electoral Commission togive the Secretary of State advice as to such of the following matters as theSecretary of State thinks appropriate—
			the electoral areas into which the region is to be divided for the purposesof the election of members to any assembly established following thereferendum;
			the number of electoral areas;
			the name by which each electoral area is to be known;
			the total number of members to be elected to the assembly.
		For the purposes of subsection (3) the direction—
			may specify maximum and minimum numbers or total numbers (as the case maybe);
			may require the advice to be given in respect of a specified number ofoptions.
		A direction given under this section may be varied (whether or not withinthe period of two years mentioned in subsection (2)) by a subsequentdirection.
	Preparation and submission of advice
		A direction given to the Electoral Commission under section 21 must specifythe timetable in accordance with which any thing must be done in connectionwith the advice.
		As soon as is reasonably practicable after receiving a direction theElectoral Commission must take such steps as they think sufficient to securethat persons who may be interested in the subject matter of the advice areinformed of—
			the direction;
			the period specified in the timetable within which representations as tothe subject matter must be made to them.
		Before submitting their advice the Commission must—
			take account of any representations made to them as mentioned in subsection(2)(b);
			prepare draft advice;
			take such steps as they think sufficient to secure that persons who may beinterested in the advice are informed of the draft and of the period specifiedin the timetable within which representations as to the draft advice must bemade to them;
			deposit copies of the draft advice at the principal offices of every countycouncil and district council in the region;
			take account of representations made to them as mentioned in paragraph (c).
		Not later than the date specified in the timetable for the submission oftheir advice the Commission must—
			submit their advice to the Secretary of State;
			take such steps as they think sufficient to secure that persons who may beinterested in the advice are informed of it and of the period specified in thetimetable within which it may be inspected;
			deposit copies of the advice at the principal offices of every countycouncil and district council in the region.
		The copies deposited under subsections (3)(d) and (4)(c) must be keptavailable for inspection by members of the public at the offices concerned inaccordance with the timetable.
		If the region to which the advice relates includes the Isles of Scilly thecopies must also be deposited under subsections (3)(d) and (4)(c) at theprincipal office of the Council of the Isles of Scilly, and subsection (5)applies accordingly.
	Electoral Commission exercise of functions
		In carrying out their functions under this Part the Electoral Commission musthave regard (in particular) to—
			the need to reflect the identities and interests of local communities;
			the need to secure that the number of electors for an electoral area for anassembly is as near as is reasonably practicable to the number of electors forthe other electoral areas (taking account, where appropriate, of specialgeographical considerations);
			guidance given by the Secretary of State.
	Payments to Electoral Commission
		The Secretary of State may pay to the Electoral Commission such amount ashe decides is the amount required by them to carry out their functions underthis Part.
		A payment under subsection (1) must be treated as income received by theCommission for the purposes of paragraph 14(1) of Schedule 1 to the PoliticalParties, Elections and Referendums Act [2000 (c.41)](/id/ukpga/2000/41?view=plain "Go to item of legislation").
